Scrum - Roles Workbook

Roles
Scrum Master	Product Owner	Scrum Team

Scrum Development Team
Composition	Professionals who build the product increment
Organization	Self-organizing
Cross-functional	Yes — all skills needed to deliver a “Done” increment each Sprint

Responsible to:	The Scrum Team and the Sprint Goal
Authority	Decide how work is done and how much work is pulled into a Sprint
Size	Typically 3–9 Developers

Product Owner
Owner of Artifact?	Product Backlog
Product Backlog  Grooming	Ensures backlog is ordered, clear, and ready
Clarifies acceptance criteria and priorities

Collects	Requirements, feedback, business needs, stakeholder input

Attends Sprint
Planning Meeting	Yes — explains backlog items and priorities
Accountability	Maximizing product value
Backlog ordering and transparency

Scrum Master
Coach—Servant Leader	Coaches team and organization in Scrum theory and practice
Shields Team	Protects team from distractions and outside interference
Deals w/Obstacles	Removes impediments and escalates blockers when needed
Daily Standup Role	Facilitates if needed, ensures event happens, does not lead the work
Team Velocity	Helps team understand and use velocity appropriately
Assist Product Owner	Helps with backlog refinement, stakeholder collaboration, and Scrum adoption


Velocity
Definition	The amount of work completed by the team in a Sprint
Calculated by:	Total story points (or estimates) of completed backlog items
Purpose	Forecasting future work and release planning

Team Velocity
How often calculated.	At the end of each Sprint
Calculated by:	Average completed work over multiple Sprints
Purpose	Helps the team plan how much work they can realistically take on


Capacity
Definition	The amount of work a team can handle in a Sprint based on availability
Purpose	Adjust Sprint commitments for vacations, holidays, or reduced availability

